<doc id="398785" wikidata="Q5298236" url="?curid=398785" title="Dorothea Brande">
<text>Dorothea Brande (1892–1948) was an American writer and editor in New York City.

==Biography==
She was born in Chicago on 12 January 1892 as Alice Dorothea Alden Thompson. In 1916 she married fellow Chicago newspaper reporter Herbert Brande and divorced sometime before 1930.

She attended the University of Chicago, the Lewis Institute in Chicago (later merged with Armour Institute of Technology to become Illinois Institute of Technology), and the University of Michigan where she earned her Phi Beta Kappa.

Her book &quot;Becoming a Writer&quot;, published in 1934, is still in print and offers advice for beginning and sustaining any writing enterprise. It has been widely praised by many writers. She also wrote &quot;Wake Up and Live&quot;, published in 1936, which sold more than a million copies. It was used as the inspiration for the comedy film &quot;Wake Up and Live&quot; in 1937.

While she was serving as associate editor of &quot;The American Review&quot; in 1936, she married that journal&#x27;s owner and editor, Seward Collins. Collins also served as the managing editor of &quot;The Bookman&quot;. Collins was a prominent literary figure in New York and a proponent of an American version of fascism.

Dorothea Collins (Dorothea Brande) died in Boston on 17 December 1948.

== Books, short stories, articles, essays and other media ==
BOOKS

&quot;&quot; (1934) - A guide for aspiring writers, offering practical advice and psychological insights into the creative process.

&quot;Beauty Vanishes&quot; (1935) - This is a poignant story that explores themes of fleeting beauty, identity, and the societal pressures on women. The narrative centers around a once beautiful woman, now past her prime, who grapples with the loss of her physical attractiveness.

&quot;Most Beautiful Lady&quot; (1935) - A novel exploring themes of beauty and human relationships.

&quot;&quot; (1936) - A self-help book encouraging readers to overcome their fears and live a more fulfilling life.

&quot;Letters to Philippa&quot; (1937) - A collection of letters offering insights into her thoughts on life and creativity.

&#x27;My Invincible Aunt&quot; (1938) - This is a story that portrays the life and character of an elderly woman who embodies resilience, strength, and an indomitable spirit. The story highlights her unwavering determination and the impact she has on those around her.

