<doc id="398874" wikidata="Q427018" url="?curid=398874" title="Associated bundle">
<text>In mathematics, the theory of fiber bundles with a structure group formula_1 (a topological group) allows an operation of creating an associated bundle, in which the typical fiber of a bundle changes from formula_2 to formula_3, which are both topological spaces with a group action of formula_1. For a fiber bundle formula_5 with structure group formula_1, the transition functions of the fiber (i.e., the cocycle) in an overlap of two coordinate systems formula_7 and formula_8 are given as a formula_1-valued function formula_10 on formula_11. One may then construct a fiber bundle formula_12 as a new fiber bundle having the same transition functions, but possibly a different fiber.

==An example==

A simple case comes with the Möbius strip, for which formula_1 is the cyclic group of order 2, formula_14. We can take as formula_5 any of: the real number line formula_16, the interval formula_17, the real number line less the point 0, or the two-point set formula_18. The action of formula_1 on these (the non-identity element acting as formula_20 in each case) is comparable, in an intuitive sense. We could say that more formally in terms of gluing two rectangles formula_21 and formula_22 together: what we really need is the data to identify formula_17 to itself directly &quot;at one end&quot;, and with the twist over &quot;at the other end&quot;. This data can be written down as a patching function, with values in formula_1. The associated bundle construction is just the observation that this data does just as well for formula_18 as for formula_17.

==Construction==
In general it is enough to explain the transition from a bundle with fiber formula_5, on which formula_1 acts, to the associated principal bundle (namely the bundle where the fiber is formula_1, considered to act by translation on itself). For then we can go from formula_2 to formula_3, via the principal bundle. Details in terms of data for an open covering are given as a case of descent.

This section is organized as follows. We first introduce the general procedure for producing an associated bundle, with specified fibre, from a given fibre bundle. This then specializes to the case when the specified fibre is a principal homogeneous space for the left action of the group on itself, yielding the associated principal bundle. If, in addition, a right action is given on the fibre of the principal bundle, we describe how to construct any associated bundle by means of a fibre product construction.

===Associated bundles in general===
Let formula_32 be a fiber bundle over a topological space formula_33 with structure group formula_1 and typical fibre formula_5. By definition, there is a left action of formula_1 (as a transformation group) on the fibre formula_5. Suppose furthermore that this action is effective.
There is a local trivialization of the bundle formula_38 consisting of an open cover formula_39 of formula_33, and a collection of fibre mapsformula_41such that the transition maps are given by elements of formula_1. More precisely, there are continuous functions formula_43 such thatformula_44 

Now let formula_12 be a specified topological space, equipped with a continuous left action of formula_1. Then the bundle associated with formula_38 with fibre formula_12 is a bundle formula_49 with a local trivialization subordinate to the cover formula_39 whose transition functions are given byformula_51where the formula_1-valued functions formula_53 are the same as those obtained from the local trivialization of the original bundle formula_38. 
This definition clearly respects the cocycle condition on the transition functions, since in each case they are given by the same system of formula_1-valued functions. (Using another local trivialization, and passing to a common refinement if necessary, the formula_56 transform via the same coboundary.) Hence, by the fiber bundle construction theorem, this produces a fibre bundle formula_49 with fibre formula_12 as claimed.

===Principal bundle associated with a fibre bundle===
As before, suppose that formula_38 is a fibre bundle with structure group formula_1. In the special case when formula_1 has a free and transitive left action on formula_12, so that formula_12 is a principal homogeneous space for the left action of formula_1 on itself, then the associated bundle formula_49 is called the principal formula_1-bundle associated with the fibre bundle formula_38. If, moreover, the new fibre formula_12 is identified with formula_1 (so that formula_12 inherits a right action of formula_1 as well as a left action), then the right action of formula_1 on formula_12 induces a right action of formula_1 on formula_49. With this choice of identification, formula_49 becomes a principal bundle in the usual sense. Note that, although there is no canonical way to specify a right action on a principal homogeneous space for formula_1, any two such actions will yield principal bundles which have the same underlying fibre bundle with structure group formula_1 (since this comes from the left action of formula_1), and isomorphic as formula_1-spaces in the sense that there is a formula_1-equivariant isomorphism of bundles relating the two.

In this way, a principal formula_1-bundle equipped with a right action is often thought of as part of the data specifying a fibre bundle with structure group formula_1, since to a fibre bundle one may construct the principal bundle via the associated bundle construction. One may then, as in the next section, go the other way around and derive any fibre bundle by using a fibre product.

===Fiber bundle associated with a principal bundle===

Let formula_84 be a principal &quot;G&quot;-bundle and let formula_85 be a continuous left action of formula_1 on a space formula_5 (in the smooth category, we should have a smooth action on a smooth manifold). Without loss of generality, we can take this action to be effective.

Define a right action of formula_1 on formula_89 via
:formula_90
We then identify by this action to obtain the space formula_91. Denote the equivalence class of formula_92 by formula_93. Note that
:formula_94
Define a projection map formula_95 by formula_96. Note that this is well-defined.

Then formula_95 is a fiber bundle with fiber formula_5 and structure group formula_1. The transition functions are given by formula_100 where formula_101 are the transition functions of the principal bundle formula_102.

This construction can also be seen categorically.
More precisely, there are two continuous maps formula_103, given by acting with formula_1 on the right on formula_102 and on the left on formula_5.
The associated vector bundle formula_107 is then the coequalizer of these maps.

==Reduction of the structure group==
The companion concept to associated bundles is the reduction of the structure group of a formula_1-bundle formula_109. We ask whether there is an formula_110-bundle formula_111, such that the associated formula_1-bundle is formula_109, up to isomorphism. More concretely, this asks whether the transition data for formula_109 can consistently be written with values in formula_110. In other words, we ask to identify the image of the associated bundle mapping (which is actually a functor).

===Examples of reduction===

Examples for vector bundles include: the introduction of a &quot;metric&quot; resulting in reduction of the structure group from a general linear group formula_116 to an orthogonal group formula_117; and the existence of complex structure on a real bundle resulting in reduction of the structure group from real general linear group formula_118 to complex general linear group formula_119.

Another important case is finding a decomposition of a vector bundle formula_120 of rank formula_121 as a Whitney sum (direct sum) of sub-bundles of rank formula_122 and formula_123, resulting in reduction of the structure group from formula_124 to formula_125.

One can also express the condition for a foliation to be defined as a reduction of the tangent bundle to a block matrix subgroup - but here the reduction is only a necessary condition, there being an &quot;integrability condition&quot; so that the Frobenius theorem applies.

